# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: beach-volleyball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:beach-volleyball/1993-world-games] The **1993 World Games** (Dutch: *1993 Wereldspelen*), the fourth World Games, were an international multi-sport event held in The Hague, Netherlands.
[src:beach-volleyball/1993-world-games] 155 titles were awarded in 23 sports (not including invitational sports — aikido, equestrian vaulting, indoor tug of war, baton twirling and barefoot waterski).
[src:beach-volleyball/1993-world-games] The medal tally during the fourth World Games is as follows.
[src:beach-volleyball/1993-world-games] Germany finished at the top of the final medal table.
[src:beach-volleyball/1993-world-games] There were two gold medals (and zero silver medals) awarded in five of the acrobatic gymnastics events because of ties for first place.
[src:beach-volleyball/1993-world-games] There were two bronze medals awarded in the karate kumite (10) and taekwondo (12) events and one of the acrobatic gymnastics events.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The **1996 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the XXVI Olympiad**, also known as **Atlanta 1996** and commonly referred to as the **Centennial Olympic Games**) were an international multi-sport event held from July 19 to August 4, 1996, in Atlanta, Georgia, United States.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] These were the fourth Summer Olympics to be hosted by the United States, making it the first country to have three different cities host the Summer Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] It also marked the 100th anniversary of the 1896 Summer Olympics in Athens, the inaugural edition of the modern Olympic Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] These were also the first Summer Olympics to be held in a different year than the Winter Olympics since the Winter Olympics commenced in 1924, as part of a new IOC practice implemented in 1994 to hold the Summer and Winter Games in alternating, even-numbered years.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Games were the first of the two consecutive Summer Olympics to be held in a predominantly English-speaking country, preceding the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] These were also the last Summer Olympics to be held in North America until 2028, when Los Angeles will host the games for the third time.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] A total of 24 countries made their Summer Olympic debuts in Atlanta, including 11 former Soviet republics participating for the first time as independent nations.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] With a total of 101 medals, the United States topped both the gold and overall medal count for the first time since 1984 (and for the first time since 1968 in a non-boycotted Summer Olympics), also winning the most gold (44) and silver (32) medals out of all the participating nations.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The Games were marred by violence on July 27, 1996, when a pipe bomb was detonated at Centennial Olympic Park (which had been built to serve as a public focal point for the festivities), killing two and injuring 111.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Years later, Eric Rudolph confessed to the bombing and a series of related terrorist attacks, and was sentenced to life in prison.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Nonetheless, the 1996 Olympics turned a profit, helped by record revenue from sponsorship deals and broadcast rights, and a reliance on private funding, among other factors.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] There were 8.3 million tickets sold for events at this Olympics, a record broken only in 2024.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] There was some criticism of the perceived over-commercialization of the Games, with other issues raised by European officials, such as the availability of food and transport.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Atlanta was selected on September 18, 1990, in Tokyo, Japan, over Athens, Belgrade, Manchester, Melbourne, and Toronto at the 96th IOC Session.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The city entered the competition as a dark horse, being up against stiff competition.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The US media also criticized Atlanta as a second-tier city and complained of Georgia's Confederate history.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] However, the IOC Evaluation Commission ranked Atlanta's infrastructure and facilities the highest, while IOC members said that it could guarantee large television revenues similar to the success of the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles, the most recent Olympics in the United States.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Additionally, former US ambassador to the UN and Atlanta mayor Andrew Young touted Atlanta's civil rights history and reputation for racial harmony.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Young also wanted to showcase a reformed American South.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The strong economy of Atlanta and improved race relations in the South helped to impress the IOC officials.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Coca-Cola, a long-standing partner of the Olympics, was also a strong advocate to bring the Games to its hometown.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games (ACOG) also proposed a substantial revenue-sharing with the IOC, USOC, and other NOCs.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] This would be Toronto's fourth failed attempt since 1960 (tried in 1960, 1964, and 1976, but was defeated by Rome, Tokyo and Montreal).
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Greece, the home of the ancient and first modern Olympics, was considered by many observers the "natural choice" for the Centennial Games, due to its "divine right" in history.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Athens bid chairman Spyros Metaxas gave repeated warnings to the IOC and demanded to give them the games to mark the centennial, saying "You don't hold a 100th birthday in someone else's home.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] However, the Athens bid was described as "arrogant and poorly prepared," being regarded as "not being up to the task of coping with the modern and risk-prone extravaganza" of the current Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The total cost of the 1996 Summer Olympics was estimated to be around US$1.7 billion.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] In total, the Games turned a profit of $19 million.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The cost for Atlanta 1996 compares with costs of $4.6 billion for Rio 2016, $40–44 billion for Beijing 2008, and $51 billion for Sochi 2014 Winter Olympics (the most expensive Olympic Games without differentiating between summer and winter in history).
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The average cost for the Summer Games since 1960 is $5.2 billion.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] ACOG budgeted $32.7 million for Atlanta Police Department and Georgia Department of Public Safety services during the games. $70 million in funding came from the U.S. federal government for additional services, including 500 additional federal agents.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Transportation relied heavily on an expanded MARTA rail and 3,000 additional buses borrowed from nationwide transit agencies.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Ticketed events came with free public transportation.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Shuttles were provided for VIPs, athletes and olympic officials.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] These shuttles connected remote Park 'N Ride lots, central terminals, and specific competition venues.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The city implemented new High-Occupancy Vehicle lanes on I-75 and I-85 highways and coordinated traffic from a centralized Traffic Management Center to handle the daily crowds that often exceeded 500,000 people.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The games were challenged by driver shortages, route navigation errors, and logistical delays.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Events of the 1996 Games were held in a completely decentralized way using mostly existing facilities that were not built for the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Most of the events were held in the so-called Olympic Ring, a 3 mi (4.8 km) circle from the center of Atlanta.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Others were held at Stone Mountain, about 20 miles (32 km) outside of the city.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] In many cases, it was decided to remove events from the Atlanta Metropolitan Region to save money, while in others the calendar was a difficulty, as was the case with association football (soccer) which ended up having its host cities spread across the Southeastern United States region.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] During early planning stages in 1992, Payne and the ACOG wanted a golf event to be held at Augusta National Golf Club.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Initially, Augusta agreed, but protests from civil rights leaders and politicians against the club's strict admission policies led to the collapse of the idea.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The Olympic Arts Festival offered 200 ticketed events, including more than 20 exhibitions in local institutions, museums, and gallery spaces.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] More than 3,000 artists participated during the two weeks of the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] There were numerous free events including a daily series of music at Centennial Olympic Park, called "Southern Crossroads".
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] In 1994, African-American artist Kevin Cole was commissioned to create the Coca-Cola Centennial Olympic Wall, and the 15-story mural took two years to complete.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The Olympiad's official theme, "Summon the Heroes", was written by John Williams, making it the third Olympiad at that point for which he had composed (official composer in 1984, NBC's coverage composer in 1988).
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony featured Céline Dion singing "The Power of the Dream", the theme song of the 1996 Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The closing ceremony featured Gloria Estefan singing "Reach", the official theme song of the 1996 Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The torch relay was run from April 27 to July 19, leading up to the Games in Atlanta.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The route covered 26,875 kilometers (16,699 mi) across the United States.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The relay involved over 12,000 torchbearers, including Muhammad Ali, who was chosen to ignite the flame at the opening ceremony.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] 8.32 million tickets were sold, a record recently broken by Paris 2024.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Ticket sales brought in $420 million for the ACOG, 1/4 of its operating budget.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The "Look of the Games" design for Atlanta 1996 was named "Quilt of Leaves".
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The graphic identity featured a quilting leaf pattern.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Representing a city coming together—with laurel leaves.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The "Quilt of Leaves" theme appeared across official venues, signage, tickets, credentials, and even physically minted into the back of the Atlanta 1996 Olympic Medals.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The logo was designed by Landor Associates, it featured the Olympic flame and stars in five vibrant colors above the number 100.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The base resembled a classical Greek column to celebrate the centennial of the modern Olympic Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The main backdrop color was: *Georgia forest green*.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] It represented green laurels branches worn by winners in ancient Greece as well as Atlanta being nicknamed "city of trees".
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The colors palette featured *khaki gold*, *tomato orange*, *magenta*, *blue* and *purple*.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Atlanta's Olympic slogan "Come Celebrate Our Dream" was written by Jack Arogeti, a managing director at McCann-Erickson in Atlanta at the time.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The slogan was selected from more than 5,000 submitted by the public to the Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Izzy was an abstract, amorphous tech-generated blue fantasy figure character wearing white gloves and red shoes.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] In contrast to the standing tradition of mascots of national or regional significance to the city hosting.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Created by John Ryan, an Atlanta animator from the DESIGNefx firm.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] A video game featuring the Games' mascot, *Izzy's Quest for the Olympic Rings*, was also released.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Summer Olympics relied heavily on commercial sponsorship, 111 total domestic corporate partners.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Company was the exclusive provider of soft drinks at Olympics venues, and built an attraction known as Coca-Cola Olympic City for the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] As part of a sponsorship agreement with Columbia TriStar Television, the syndicated game shows *Jeopardy!* and *Wheel of Fortune* both produced episodes with Olympics tie-ins (including branded memorabilia and contests) for broadcast between April and July 1996.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] These included a *Jeopardy!* international tournament, and three weeks of *Wheel of Fortune* episodes filmed on-location at Atlanta's Fox Theatre.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The Atlanta organizing committee threatened legal actions against advertisers whose marketing implied an official association with the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Several non-sponsors set up marketing activities in areas near venues, such as Samsung (competing with Motorola), which ambushed the Games with its "96 Expo".
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The city of Atlanta had also licensed street vendors to sell products from competitors to Olympic sponsors.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Nike also opened a pop-up store known as the Nike Center near the Athletes' Village, which distributed Nike-branded flags to visitors (presumably to be used at events).
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] IOC marketing director Michael Payne expressed concern for the campaign, believing that athletes could perceive them as being an insult to their accomplishments.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Payne and the United States Olympic Committee's marketing director, John Krimsky, met with Howard Slusher, a subordinate of Nike co-founder Phil Knight.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Faced with these threats, Nike agreed to retract most of its negative advertising and public relations stunts.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] A total of 197 nations, all of the then-existing and recognized National Olympic Committees, were represented at the 1996 Games, and the combined total of athletes was about 10,318.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Twenty-four countries made their Olympic debut this year, including eleven of the ex-Soviet countries that competed as part of the Unified Team in 1992.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Russia participated in the Summer Olympics separately from the other countries of the former Soviet Union for the first time since 1912 (when it was the Russian Empire).
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Russia had been a member of the Unified Team at the 1992 Summer Olympics together with 11 post-Soviet states.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia competed as *Yugoslavia*.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] After missing the 1992 Summer Games Afghanistan and Cambodia returned to send delegations to Atlanta.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The 14 countries making their Olympic debut were: Azerbaijan, Burundi, Cape Verde, Comoros, Dominica, Guinea-Bissau, Macedonia, Nauru, Palestinian Authority, Saint Kitts and Nevis, Saint Lucia, São Tomé and Príncipe, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The ten countries making their Summer Olympic debut (after competing at the 1994 Winter Olympics in Lillehammer) were: Armenia, Belarus, Czech Republic, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Slovakia, Ukraine and Uzbekistan.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The Czech Republic and Slovakia attended the games as independent nations for the first time since the breakup of Czechoslovakia, while the rest of the nations that made their Summer Olympic debut were formerly part of the Soviet Union.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] 10,339 athletes from 197 NOCs participated in the 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The ceremony began with a 60-second countdown, which included footage from all of the previous Olympic Games at twenty-two seconds.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] There was then a flashback to the closing ceremony of the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona, showing the then president of the IOC, Juan Antonio Samaranch, inviting the athletes to compete in Atlanta in 1996.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Then, spirits ascended in the northwest corner of the stadium, each representing one of the colors in the Olympic rings.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The spirits called the tribes of the world which, after mixed percussion, formed the Olympic rings while the youth of Atlanta formed the number 100.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Famed film score composer John Williams wrote the official overture for the 1996 Olympics, called "Summon the Heroes"; this was his second overture for Olympic games, the first being "Olympic Fanfare and Theme" written for the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Céline Dion performed David Foster's official 1996 Olympics song "The Power of the Dream", accompanied by Foster on the piano, the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra and the Centennial Choir (comprising Morehouse College Glee Club, Spelman College Glee Club and the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra Chorus).
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Gladys Knight sang Georgia's official state song, "Georgia on My Mind".
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] There was another showcase entitled "Summertime" which focused on Atlanta and the Old South, emphasizing its beauty, spirit, music, history, culture, and rebirth after the American Civil War.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The ceremony also featured a memorable dance tribute to the athletes and to the goddesses of victory of the ancient Greek Olympics, using silhouette imagery.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The accompanying music, "The Tradition of the Games", was composed by Basil Poledouris.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Muhammad Ali lit the Olympic cauldron and later received a replacement gold medal for his boxing victory in the 1960 Summer Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] For the torch ceremony, more than 10,000 Olympic torches were manufactured by the American Meter Company, electroplated by Klein Plating Works, and polished by Erie Plating Company.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Each torch weighed about 3.5 pounds (1.6 kg) and was made primarily of aluminum, with a Georgia pecan wood handle and gold ornamentation.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The city of Savannah, Georgia, host of the yachting events, also held their own opening ceremony on the first day of their competitions.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The event was headlined by a performance by country musician Trisha Yearwood.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Summer Olympic program featured 271 events in 26 sports.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Softball, beach volleyball and mountain biking debuted on the Olympic program, together with women's football, lightweight events in rowing, Women's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay in swimming, the Women's épée in fencing and the group all-around event in rhythmic gymnastics.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1996 Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Domestic network NBC bought the broadcasting rights for US$456 million.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The European Broadcasting Union paid US$240 million.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Olympics were marred by the Centennial Olympic Park bombing, which occurred on July 27.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Security guard Richard Jewell discovered the pipe bomb and immediately notified law enforcement, helping to evacuate as many people as possible from the area before it exploded.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Although Jewell's quick actions are credited for saving many lives, the bombing killed spectator Alice Hawthorne, wounded 111 others, and caused the death of Melih Uzunyol by a heart attack.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Jewell was later considered a suspect in the bombing but was never charged, and he was cleared in October 1996.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Fugitive Eric Rudolph was arrested in May 2003 and charged with the Olympic Park bombing as well as the bombings of two abortion clinics and a gay nightclub.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Preparations for the Olympics lasted more than seven years and had an economic impact of at least US$5.14 billion.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Over two million visitors came to Atlanta, and approximately 3.5 billion people around the world watched at least some of the events on television.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Although marred by the tragedy of the Centennial Olympic Park bombing, the Games were a financial success, due in part to TV rights contracts and sponsorships at record levels.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Atlanta also set a new record for the most tickets sold at a single Games (8.3 million), and held it until 2024.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Beyond international recognition, the Games resulted in many modern infrastructure improvements.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The mid-rise dormitories built for the Olympic Village, which became the first residential housing for Georgia State University (Georgia State Village), are now used by the Georgia Institute of Technology (North Avenue Apartments).
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] As designed, the Centennial Olympic Stadium was converted into Turner Field after the Paralympics, which became the home of the Atlanta Braves Major League Baseball team from 1997 to 2016.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The Braves' former home, Atlanta–Fulton County Stadium, was demolished in 1997 and the site became a parking lot for Turner Field; the Omni Coliseum was demolished the same year to make way for State Farm Arena.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The city's permanent memorial to the 1996 Olympics is Centennial Olympic Park, which was built as a focal point for the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The park initiated a revitalization of the surrounding area and now serves as the hub for Atlanta's tourism district.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] In November 2016, a commemorative plaque was unveiled for Centennial Olympic Park to honor the 20th anniversary of the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Following the Braves' departure from Turner Field to Truist Park in 2017, Georgia State University acquired the former Olympic Stadium and surrounding parking lots.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] It reconfigured the stadium for a second time into Center Parc Stadium for its college football team.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Olympic cauldron was originally built and placed at the intersection of Fulton Street and Capitol Avenue, near the Centennial Olympic Stadium.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] After the Paralympics, in order to make room for the stadium conversion, the Olympic cauldron was moved (except its ramp, which was demolished) to the intersection of Capitol Avenue and Fulton Street in 1997, where it has stayed since.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Since Georgia State University's acquisition of the former Olympic Stadium and surrounding lots, there has been proposals and growing calls to move the Olympic cauldron to Centennial Olympic Park.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The Olympic cauldron was re-lit in February 2020 for the 2020 U.S.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Olympics are the most recent edition of the Summer Olympics to be held in the United States.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Los Angeles will host the 2028 Summer Olympics, 32 years after the Games were held in Atlanta.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] In 1997, Athens was awarded the 2004 Summer Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Along with addressing the shortcomings of its 1996 bid, it was lauded for its efforts to promote the traditional values of the Olympic Games, which some IOC observers felt had been lost due to the over-commercialization of the 1996 Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] However, the 2004 Games heavily relied on public funding and eventually failed to make a profit, which some have claimed contributed to the financial crisis in Greece.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The financial struggles faced by many later Games, such as the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin and the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, have caused some to offer more positive reappraisals of the management of the 1996 Summer Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] Former JPMorgan Chase president (and torchbearer) Kabir Sehgal noted that in contrast to many later Olympics, those of 1996 were financially viable, had a positive economic impact on the city, and most of the facilities constructed continued to be used after the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1996-summer-olympics] The 2028 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles will rely almost entirely on private funding, with the city of Los Angeles and state of California each intending to provide up to $250 million in funding in the event of shortfalls, and the U.S. federal government providing funding solely for security.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] The sporting events commenced on 30 November 1998, a week earlier than the opening ceremony.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] It is a last time that the multi-sport event would be held in Bangkok until the 2007 Summer Universiade.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] Bangkok was awarded the right on September 26, 1990, defeating Taipei, Taiwan and Jakarta, Indonesia to host the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] It was the first city to hosted the Asian Games for four times, but was the first time that the city make a bid to host.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] The last three editions it hosted were in 1966, 1970 and 1978 (in the latter two cases stepping in to prevent the Games from being cancelled due to problems with the elected hosts).
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] The event was opened by Bhumibol Adulyadej, the king of Thailand, at the Rajamangala Stadium.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] The final medal tally was led by China, followed by South Korea, Japan and the host Thailand.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] Thailand set a new record with 24 gold medals.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] Japanese Athletics Koji Ito was announced as the most valuable player (MVP) of the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] For Thailand, it was considered one of its remarkable achievement in sports development throughout the country's modern history.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] Three cities placed a bid for the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] All three, Taipei (Taiwan), Jakarta (Indonesia) and Bangkok (Thailand) submitted their formal bid in 1989.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] It was the first time that Thailand has presented a bid for host the Asian Games, as Bangkok was the default host of previous three games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] The vote was held on September 27, 1990, at the China Palace Tower Hotel in Beijing, China, during the 9th Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) General Assembly held during the 1990 Asian Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] All 37 members voted, with voting held in secret ballot.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] It was announced that Bangkok won an Asian Games bid process for the first time.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] Though the vote results were not released, was leaked to the press that Bangkok won by 20–10–7.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] Bangkok became the first city to have staged the Asian Games for four editions, following 1966, 1970 and 1978, and this was the first time that the city had put a bid for the event.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] According to United Press International news report, preparations for the games including the construction and renovation of three main stadiums and an athletes' village, cost an estimated 6 billion Thai baht (US$167 million).
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] The official emblem of the games combines elements from Thai stupas and pagodas, the letter "A", which means either "Asia" or "Athletes", and the logo of the Olympic Council of Asia.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] It symbolises the knowledge, intelligence and athletic prowess of Thailand.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] The official mascot of the games is an elephant named **Chai-Yo** (ไชโย), the equivalent of "hurrah" in Thai.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] Elephants are known and admired among Thais for their strength and nobility.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] The opening ceremony started at 17:00 local time on December 6, 1998.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] It was attended by King of Thailand, Bhumibol Adulyadej, President of the International Olympic Committee Juan Antonio Samaranch and President of the OCA Sheikh Ahmed Al-Fahad Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] The nations entered in alphabetic order of their country names in Thai during the parade of nations.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] National Olympic Committees (NOCs) are named according to their official IOC designations and arranged according to their official IOC country codes in 1998.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] The top ten ranked NOCs at these Games are listed below.
[src:beach-volleyball/1998-asian-games] The host nation, Thailand, is highlighted.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Canoeing competitions started the day before the games officially began.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Approximately 5,000 athletes from 42 nations participated in the games to vie for a total of 330 medal events in 34 sports and 42 disciplines.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Financially, the 1999 games were a success, generating a surplus of $8.9 million through a combination of fiscal restraint and the contribution of nearly 20,000 volunteers.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] The 1999 Pan American Games were the second Pan American Games hosted by Canada and Winnipeg.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Previously, Winnipeg hosted the 1967 Pan American Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Winnipeg beat both Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic, and Bogotá, Colombia in 1994 to win hosting rights for the event.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] In 1988, a delegation from Winnipeg announced that once it got approval from the Canadian Olympic Association, the city would submit a bid to host the 1999 Pan American Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] On December 5, 1992, Winnipeg secured the Canadian bidding rights, defeating Toronto by one vote.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Other Canadian cities in the running were Halifax, Edmonton, and Sherbrooke.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Toronto would later go on to host the 2015 Pan American Games, 16 years later.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Any country that had previously held the games was allotted two votes; those countries were Argentina, Brazil, Mexico, United States, and Venezuela, making 50 votes in total, and a city needed a majority vote (26) to win.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Canada and Colombia were not allowed to vote, as they each had a city making a bid.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] After the first round of voting, Bogotá was eliminated having the fewest voting with 10 votes.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] In the second round, Winnipeg and Santo Domingo reached a 25-to-25 tie.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Santo Domingo later won the rights to the next games in 2003.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] A total of 32 sporting venues were used for the games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] The Pan Am Pool, built for the 1967 games, featured in the 1999 games for all aquatic events.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] The venue underwent a $3.3 million renovation for the games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Other new venues included the $8.7 million Investors Group Athletic Centre built for multiple sports and the $12 million CanWest Global Park for the baseball competition.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] The main stadium for the games was the Winnipeg Stadium, which staged the ceremonies and the beach volleyball competitions.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] The Winnipeg Velodrome, also built for the 1967 games, had become obsolete and disused for cycling and so was demolished prior to the 1999 games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] The cycling venue was a temporary facility at Red River Exhibition Park.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] The opening ceremony of the 1999 Pan American Games took place on Friday July 23, 1999, beginning at 19:30 p.m.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] CDT and lasted for two hours and forty-five minutes at the Winnipeg Stadium.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] A crowd of 30,000 spectators attended the ceremony.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Seven Aboriginal Canadians, who were denied entrance into the 1967 Pan American Games, also in Winnipeg, this time entered the stadium with the torch while on canoes.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Former Olympians Alwyn Morris and Silken Laumann were the final two torchbearers who lit the cauldron.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] A total of 3,400 performers took part in the ceremony, including the Winnipeg Symphony Orchestra and singer Jeremy Kushnier.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Singer Chantal Kreviazuk sang the national anthem, O Canada as part of the ceremony.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Governor General Roméo LeBlanc officially opened the games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] One of the dignitaries in attendance was Anne, Princess Royal.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Beach volleyball and inline hockey made their Pan American Games debut.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] While women's tournaments in football, and water polo were held for the first time.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Perhaps the greatest drug scandal in the sport of track and field, since Ben Johnson's disqualification at the 1988 Summer Olympics, occurred here when Javier Sotomayor the current high jump world record holder tested positive for cocaine.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] A Cuban national hero, his subsequent suspension was fought from the highest levels, with Fidel Castro claiming it was an anti-Cuba conspiracy staged by the United States.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Despite a second positive test for cocaine a few months later, Sotomayor eventually had his suspension reduced by a year, just in time to win the silver medal at the 2000 Summer Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] A year later he retired, when he faced another positive drug test.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Canada was stripped of its gold medal for inline hockey when the team's goaltender Steve Vézina tested positive for multiple banned substances.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] The 1999 Games' mascot features two birds named *Pato* (Wood duck) and *Lorita* (Parrot).
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Television broadcasts of the games were produced by Paul Graham.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] The 1999 Pan Am games have been "seen by many Winnipeggers as a chance to put their city squarely in the international spotlight".
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Winnipeg mayor Glen Murray became nationally well known as a result of the Games and thanks to extensive coverage by the CBC, anchored by CBC Sports' Brian Williams.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] However, the Games themselves only had mixed success, as the Pan Am Games ranked below the Olympics and Commonwealth Games in international prestige.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] The Games cost $129 million CDN and finished with a financial surplus of $8.8 million CDN.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Hosts Canada celebrated its medal haul, which was the second best after the United States.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] However, some considered Canada's results overrated, since the U.S. amassed the most medals with a mostly second-string team while Canada and Cuba had fielded their top national athletes.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Cuba also managed more golds than Canada, despite having a smaller roster.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Frequent comparisons were made to the 1967 Pan Am Games, also hosted by Winnipeg, where the United States had fielded many rising stars, such as Mark Spitz.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] By comparison, the Americans had sent their "B" team to the 1999 Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] No major U.S. networks covered the Pan Am Games, except for the Spanish-language network Univisión, while newspapers only sent second-string reporters instead and the stories never made front page news.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] Many high-profile athletes, of all nationalities, such as U.S. champion sprinters and Brazilian football players, were in Europe during these Pan Am games, taking part in professional events.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] South American nations (with the exception of Uruguay) did not send their under-23 male soccer teams after the organizing committee refused to pay appearance money to CONMEBOL.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] In 1999, the Parapan American Games were not hosted in Winnipeg, but rather in Mexico City.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-pan-american-games] The inaugural event involved 1,000 athletes from 18 countries competing in four sports.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-south-pacific-games] The **11th South Pacific Games**, also known as **Guam 1999** (Chamorro: *Guåhån 1999*), held in Santa Rita and Hagåtña, Guam from 29 May to 12 June 1999, was the eleventh edition of the South Pacific Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-south-pacific-games] Note: A number in parentheses indicate the size of a country's team (where known).
[src:beach-volleyball/1999-south-pacific-games] Note: A number in parentheses indicates how many medal events were contested in that sport.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Doha was the first city in its region and only the second in West Asia (following Tehran in 1974) to host the games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The city will host the games again in 2030.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] It was the first time that all 45 member nations of the Olympic Council of Asia took part in this event.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Also, Eurosport broadcast the event, marking the first time that the event was broadcast outside the continent.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] 21 competition venues were used for the Games including the newly constructed Aspire Indoor Sports Complex.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The opening and closing ceremonies of the Games were held at Khalifa International Stadium.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The trampoline discipline of gymnastics, as well as chess and triathlon made their debut at the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The final medal tally was led by China, followed by South Korea and Japan.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Tajikistan, Jordan and United Arab Emirates won their first ever Asian Games gold medals.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] 7 world and 23 Asian records were broken during the games, while South Korean swimmer Park Tae-hwan was announced as the most valuable player.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Doha, Hong Kong, Kuala Lumpur and New Delhi submitted their formal bids by the deadline 30 June 2000.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Prior to the voting, evaluation committee of the OCA, headed by the then vice-president of the association Muhammad Latif Butt inspected Doha on 13 and 14 July 2000, New Delhi on 15 and 16 July 2000, Kuala Lumpur on 17 and 18 July 2000, and Hong Kong on 19 and 20 July 2000.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] On November 12, 2000, voting for the 2006 venue took place during the 19th Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) General Assembly held in Busan, South Korea.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The voting involved the 41 members of the Olympic Council of Asia and consisted of three rounds, each round eliminating one of the bidding cities.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] After the first round, New Delhi was eliminated, with only two votes.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The second round of voting, with three remaining candidates, gave Doha as the result.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Under the regulations of the OCA, a candidate which gains more than half of the available votes (at least 21 out of 41 votes) will automatically be selected as the host, and the remaining rounds of voting will be cancelled.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] When Doha gained 22 out of 41 votes this meant they were selected to host the 2006 Asian Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Most of Qatar's votes came from the unanimous support from West Asian countries.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] After the major upset, Malaysia and Hong Kong, China expressed their disappointment.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Malaysia said that the selection of Doha was ridiculous and that the selection of Doha was influenced by Qatar's economic wealth.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Qatar spent US$2.8 billion on preparing venues, including a major upgrade to the 50,000-seat Khalifa Stadium from its original 20,000-seat capacity and the construction of the Aspire indoor sports complex, the world's largest indoor multi-sports dome.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Volunteering programme of Doha 2006 Asian Games which began in July 2004 targeted 12,000 volunteers and over 30,000 applications were received.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The volunteers wore a specific uniform and are grouped at the Uniform Distribution and Accreditation Centre at the Al-Gharafa SC.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The torch relay has been integral to the Asian Games since 1958.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The plans for the Doha 2006 torch relay were revealed by the Doha Asian Games Organising Committee on 20 January 2006.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] It engaged EFM Global Logistics to handle all the logistics for the relay.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The torch of the 2006 edition weighs 1.5 kilograms and is 72 centimetres tall.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Its design was inspired by the curvaceous horns of the Arabian Oryx, featuring maroon and white colours which are the colours of the Qatari national flag.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] It symbolises the unifying spirit of competition and friendship throughout Asia.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The relay itself started on 8 October 2006 with a brief ceremony at the Doha Golf Club where the torch was lit with the theme of "Flame of Hospitality".
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] With the involvement of over 3,000 people, the torch crossed eight former Asian Games host cities and the four Gulf Cooperation Council member states.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The torch travelled back to Doha held by Sheikh Joan Bin Hamad Al-Thani, and the journey around the city itself started on 25 November 2006 and lasted until the opening ceremony of the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The first stop was in New Delhi, the birthplace of the Asian Games on 11 October 2006 where the torch's flame was fused together with the Eternal Asian Games Flame that burn at the Dhyan Chand National Stadium.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] During the fourth stop in Hiroshima on 21 October, the torch's flame was fused again but now with the Peace flame that burns at the Hiroshima Peace Memorial Park.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] In total the relay passed through 13 countries and 23 cities, visited several landmarks such as Taj Mahal and the Great Wall of China along its way to Qatar.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The relay, which totaled a distance of 50,000 kilometres in 55 days, was until today, the longest in the history of the Asian Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The emblem of the 15th Asian Games is an image of an athlete in motion which represents fearless manner of a sportsperson in face of challenges and obstacles.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The colours used in the emblem represent Qatar's landscape.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Yellow represents the crescent-shaped sand dunes of the desert, blue represents the calm sea of the Gulf and red represents the sun and warm spirit of Asia.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] An Arabian oryx named Orry served as the official mascot of the games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] It was unveiled at the Doha waterfront on 1 January 2005 in conjunction with the start of the 700-day countdown to the games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] He represents energy, determination, sportsmanship spirit, commitment, enthusiasm, participation, respect, peace and fun; he is also described as a great sportsman.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The medals of the games were designed by Dallah advertising and Gulf Media agency.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Around 3,000 medals in gold, silver and bronze were made for the games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] They featured Orry, the official Games mascot, as well as the Al Zubara Fort on the obverse and the official logo on the reverse.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] To promote the games, the organisers built a countdown clock and a giant statue of the official mascot, Orry, at the Doha Corniche.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] In addition, they also decorated the city with banners and 30 life-size versions of the mascot in a variety of different sporting poses.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Touchscreen kiosks were set up at hotels, malls and businesses in the city to provide users with Qatar tourism and the games' information and details.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] On 3 April 2005, Qatar's flag carrier, Qatar Airways signed a US$10 million agreement with the Doha Asian Games Organising Committee (DAGOC) to become the event's official airline.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] During the games, merchandises were sold at various locations in the city, including competition venues.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The Games used mostly new venues within the city.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] There were a total of 23 venues for the games, with 21 of them being competition venues and others being Main Media Centre and Athletes' village.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] After a major upgrade, Khalifa Stadium had a new running track, a new tensile fabric roof structure on its western seating and an arch on its east part.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] A temporary velodrome was built at Aspire Academy for track cycling events.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The Athletes’ Village was built on a 330,000 square metres site in the city centre, which had 32 residential buildings with 811 five-bedroom apartments for athletes and 45 for Chef-de-Missions and could accommodate 11,500 athletes and team officials.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The opening ceremony was viewed by 50,000 spectators in the Khalifa International Stadium, including VIP guests like Jacques Rogge from the International Olympic Committee, Mahmoud Ahmadinejad from Iran, Ismail Haniyeh from Palestine and Bashar al-Assad from Syria.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The opening ceremony was directed and produced by the Australian David Atkins, who also helmed the 2000 Summer Olympics opening ceremony in Sydney.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The opening ceremony showcased the importance of the culture of the Arab world in the history of Asia and referenced the region's contact with other Asian cultures.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Several musical artists such as Hong Kong's Jacky Cheung, India's Bollywood star Sunidhi Chauhan, Lebanon's Majida El Roumi and Spanish tenor José Carreras performed at the ceremony.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The ceremony ended with the lighting of the cauldron at the main stadium by Mohammed Bin Hamad Al-Thani, son of the emir and captain of the Qatar equestrian endurance team.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] At the same time, another cauldron was lit at the top of the Aspire Tower.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The games was officially opened by the Emir of Qatar, Sheikh Hamad bin Khalifa Al Thani.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] All 45 OCA members participated in the Games, including Iraq which returned to compete after its suspension was lifted.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Iraq last competed at the 1986 Asian Games and was suspended from 1990 until 2004 due to the Gulf War.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The number in parentheses indicates the number of participants that the National Olympic Committee contributed.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The sport events contested at the 2006 Asian Games are listed below.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Officially there are 46 disciplines from 39 sports in contention.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] All events listed started after the opening ceremony except badminton, baseball, basketball, football, table tennis, and volleyball, which had preliminaries before the opening ceremony.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Trampoline discipline of gymnastics, and the sports of chess and triathlon made their debut at the event.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] In the following calendar for the 2006 Asian Games, each blue box represents an event competition, such as a qualification round, on that day.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The yellow boxes represent days during which medal-awarding finals for a sport were held.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The closing ceremony featured an homage to classic Middle Eastern stories and served as a continuation of the opening ceremony.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The artistic programme starred the same young boy who played the "Seeker" in the opening ceremony.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] In the first segment, the boy flew on a magic carpet and entered a magical storybook world that paid tribute to the classic folktales of *One Thousand and One Nights*.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] This segment included references to stories featured in *The Nights* like *Ali Baba and the Forty Thieves*, *Sinbad the Sailor* and *Aladdin and the Wonderful Lamp*.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] An array of dancers, horses, and special effects were used to portray the different stories.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] In one scene, the games cauldron was extinguished when the magic carpet left the stadium.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Afterwards, there was another segment called "*Land of the Oryx*" in which various dances were performed.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] All 45 nations' athletes entered the stadium after the artistic programme was finished.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] South Korean swimmer, Park Tae-hwan was announced as the best athlete of the Games, having won seven medals, three of them being golds from the swimming competitions.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] After that, the OCA President Sheikh Ahmad Al-Fahad Al-Sabah officially announced the Games closed.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] As per tradition, the Qatari Armed Forces personnel lowered the OCA flag, which would then be carried by the students of Aspire Academy out of the stadium.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Later, the Chinese flag was raised to the Chinese National Anthem.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Sheikh Ahmad then passed the OCA flag to the mayor of Guangzhou, Zhang Guangning, as the city was to be the next Asian Games host in 2010.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] A special 10 minute handover segment called "*Oriental Charm*" was then presented to showcase Guangzhou as the next host city.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] This segment fused the traditional dances of China's performing arts with a modern setting.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Afterwards, the theme song of the games, "Triumph of the One", was performed by Lea Salonga from the Philippines.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The ceremony ended with a fireworks display that also marked the conclusion of the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] A joint venture between Host Broadcast Services and IMG Media named the Doha Asian Games Broadcast Services (DAGBS), now International Games Broadcast Services (IGBS), was set up in September 2004 and served as the games' host broadcaster after being appointed by the organiser the following month.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] It distributed 2,000 hours of the Games content to its international rights holders.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The International Broadcast Centre was constructed in Qatar International Exhibition Centre (QIEC).
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Viewers in the European continent watch the event for the first time with Eurosport as the region's broadcaster.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] South Korean equestrian athlete Kim Hyung-chil died after falling off his horse on the morning of December 7 during the cross country competition which took place in the rain.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The accident occurred at jump number eight during the cross-country stage of the three-day eventing competition.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] After the horse, named Bundaberg Black, rolled over him, he was taken to Hamad General Hospital, with his death later confirmed by the organizing committee.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Kim died at around 10.50 am, shortly before noon Qatar time.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] During the accident, he suffered from severe trauma to his head, neck and upper chest.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Kim's horse suffered a serious injury during the fall and was euthanised after the accident.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] According to South Korea National Olympic Committee president Kim Jung Kil, sources on the course said that the horse mistimed his jump in the wet conditions and slipped.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] South Korean officials are asking for an inquiry to determine if mismanagement or rain was the cause of the death.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] "In my professional opinion, neither the weather nor the footing had any bearing on this accident.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] If the horse falls, it's like two tons of bricks falling on you.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] There is nothing you can do about it," said Andy Griffiths, the Games event's technical overseer.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Christopher Hodson, vice president of the International Equestrian Federation, said the course was fit to ride when a full investigation into the accident was conducted.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Kim's father was an equestrian athlete for South Korea in the 1964 Summer Olympics in Tokyo and the younger Kim won a silver medal at the 2002 Asian Games in Busan on the same horse.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] This is the eighth death linked to the 2006 Asian Games, and the first involving an athlete.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The accident came four days after the road accident which killed Jagadammamdhu Sudanan Thampi, a 60-year-old female volunteer from India.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Despite the opening ceremony, which received some high praise, there was some criticism by some delegations and athletes.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Heavy rain poured down just after the end of opening ceremony, and many believed that the organizers did not have plans to deal with it, creating a chaotic situation.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] He went on to say that the breakdown in transportation protocols due to the rain caused the athletes to rush to the nearest bus station, exposing them to rain.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Ramirez said that he himself was a victim of pushing and shoving due to this chaos, and that because of it, he suffered from an asthma attack.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] According to one IOC insider who arrived back at his hotel soaked, this incident hurt the chances of Doha hosting the 2016 Summer Olympics, which Doha applied for on 25 October 2007, and lost on 4 June 2008 when they were eliminated from the pool.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Transportation was one of the crucial factors involved in the decision process.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Doha would have its own metro system in 2019.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] In brochures published in the lead-up to the games, the Persian Gulf was referred to as the "Arabian Gulf".
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] In response, Iranian state television accused the naming conventions to be influenced by a "Zionist" plot.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Subsequently, Iran threatened to boycott the games if the brochures were not changed.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The organizers relented and Iran competed.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The Games' organizers faced significant bed shortages due to the record number of more than 13,000 athletes and officials who attended the 2006 Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The Athletes' Village had space for only 10,500 people and was not large enough to accommodate the record amount of attendees.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] To resolve the problem, organizers contracted with three cruise ships to provide sleeping quarters.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The Football competition lost three teams due to withdrawals and a suspension, which resulted rescheduling of the format and draws.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Following the withdrawal of Maldives women's football team in early November, the women's football competition was forced to redraw to ensure both groups had an equal number of teams.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Not much later, Turkmenistan announced their withdrawal due to the lack of options available in Qatar.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Yemen also withdrew because the team was unable to afford a drug test after some of their players were accused of doping.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] India made big changes to its team close to the opening ceremonies.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] On November 22, 2006, the Indian sports dropped eight of the 32 events they had previously announced that they would be contesting in the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The dropped events were basketball, handball, sepak takraw, triathlon, ten-pin bowling and rugby sevens.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] The events were dropped due to the lack of medal hopes and to cut costs.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] As a result, 387 athletes were sent to Doha instead of the original 589 proposed by the Indian Olympic Association.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] While volleyball also had three teams withdraw from the Games, Palestine withdrew due to the travelling difficulties caused by the closure of the Gaza Strip border.
[src:beach-volleyball/2006-asian-games] Indonesia and Turkmenistan also withdrew from the tournament, for unknown reasons, just hours before their first preliminary round match.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The **13th South Pacific Games** (Samoan: *Taʻaloga Lona-Sefulu-Tolu a le Pasefika i Saute*), also known as **Apia 2007**, were held from 25 August to 8 September 2007 in Apia, Samoa.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The Games were the thirteenth to be held since the inception of the South Pacific Games in 1963, and included traditional multi-sport event disciplines, such as athletics and swimming, alongside region-specific and smaller events such as outrigger canoeing, surfing and lawn bowls.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The principal venue for the Games was Apia Park, with other events taking place at the Faleata Sporting Complex and at other locations around Samoa.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The cost of the games was reported to be US$92 million and resulted in significant government debt for Samoa due to infrastructure projects which included replacement bridges and roads.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The opening ceremony took place on 25 August 2007 at Apia Park Stadium and was performed in a traditional Samoan and Pacific style, welcoming some 5,000 athletes from 22 nations and territories to Samoa.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The ceremony was attended by Tuilaepa Aiono Sailele Malielegaoi, Prime Minister of Samoa (who also competed in the Games - *see below*), and Tuiatua Tupua Tamasese Efi, Head of State.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] Former New Zealand Idol winner Rosita Vai sang an accompaniment to the torch lighting of the ceremonial flame by Ofisa Ofisa, a Samoan weightlifter.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] Following a rest day on Sunday, the sporting events of the Games began on Monday, 27 August.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] Samoan Prime Minister Tuilaepa Aiono Sailele Malielegaoi competed for his country at the Games in the sport of target archery.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] In participating in the Games, the Prime Minister became the first *elected* leader to represent his country at a multi-sport event.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] Having taken up the sport only 5 months prior to the Games, Tuilaepa was ranked second in Samoa in the *combined bow* discipline.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The Prime Minister's son was also a reserve team member.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] On day 10 of the Games, Tuilaepa won a silver medal in the *mixed recurve team play* event.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] Problems with equipment and the lack of multi-sport event infrastructures within the region created difficulties throughout the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The decathlon was reduced to eight disciplines due to a shortage of equipment.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The poles for the pole vault were still in Melbourne after the ship due to deliver them was delayed by poor weather and the high jump was the discipline cancelled to allow the event to comply with IAAF regulations (there is no IAAF-sanctioned nine discipline event).
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] In addition, the 1500 metre race was reduced to 1 km.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The women's 400-metre hurdles and men's discus were also affected.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The lack of funding and facilities for drug testing also restricted the ability of Games authorities to run a full drug testing and anti-doping programme at the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] Only one hundred athletes (primarily in high-risk events such as bodybuilding and weightlifting) were due to be tested as samples needed to be flown overseas from Samoa to be processed at a cost of A$500 per sample.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] Fireworks due to feature in the Closing Ceremony also remained in Melbourne after difficulties transporting them by ship to Samoa.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The religious sensitivities of the host nation (which is primarily Congregationalist Christian) and other participants resulted in several controversial decisions during the organisation and running of the Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] Athletes in the women's beach volleyball event were required to wear shorts and T-shirts as opposed to the regulation bikini-style outfits to avoid offending family members and other spectators.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] It's against the law of God!" Such activity is prohibited under Samoan law and punishable by up to five years' imprisonment.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] However, the ban on homosexual intercourse was later lifted by organising committee chairman Tapasu Lueng Wai.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] A campaign to issue athletes condoms and advice on sexually transmitted infections also met with resistance from religious leaders.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The Archbishop of the Catholic Church in Samoa, Alapati Mataeliga suggested that, in doing so, the authorities were encouraging extra-marital sexual activity which was frowned upon by the church.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] Games authorities also back-tracked on plans to issue athletes with female condoms after fears it might "expose young athletes to sex." Male condoms were nevertheless distributed.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The closing ceremony for the Games again took place at Apia Park.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] Attended by some 20,000 spectators, a twelve-minute fireworks display brought proceedings to an end before hundreds of balloons were released in the colours of the Games flag which was itself duly lowered and the ceremonial flame extinguished.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The flag was then passed to New Caledonia delegates, supported by a Kanak cultural group, ahead of the 2011 Pacific Games in Noumea.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] A significant amount of the pre-Games expenditure was spent on building new facilities and upgrading those already in existence in Samoa.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] The majority of the new facilities were sited at the Faleata Sports Complex at Tuana'imato.
[src:beach-volleyball/2007-south-pacific-games] However, many Samoans feared the size of the complex and other construction would lead to the venues becoming significant white elephants after the Games were over.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Teams are allowed up to three touches to return the ball across the net, and individual players may not touch the ball twice consecutively except after a touch off an attempted block.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Making a block touch leaves only two more touches before the ball must be hit over.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The ball is put in play with a serve—a hit by the server from behind the rear court boundary over the net to the opponents.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The receiving team typically uses their three touches to pass the ball, set it up for an attack, and then attack the ball by sending it back over the net.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Meanwhile, the team on defense typically has a blocker at the net and a defender to cover the ground.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The rally continues until the ball is grounded on the playing court, goes "out", or a fault is made in the attempt to return the ball.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The team that wins the rally scores a point and serves to start the following rally.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The players serve in the same sequence throughout the match, changing server each time a rally is won by the receiving team.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beach volleyball was most likely originated in 1915 on Waikiki Beach in Hawaii, while the modern two-player game originated in Santa Monica, California, where the first volleyball courts were put up on the beach.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] It has been an Olympic sport since the 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The Fédération Internationale de Volleyball (FIVB) is the international governing body for the sport, and organizes the FIVB Beach Volleyball World Championships and the FIVB Beach Volleyball World Tour.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beach volleyball is a variant of indoor volleyball, which was invented in 1895 by William G.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beach volleyball most likely originated in 1915 on Waikiki Beach in Hawaii, at the Outrigger Canoe Club.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] According to a 1978 interview with an Outrigger Canoe Club member, George David "Dad" Center put a net up there, and the first recorded game of beach volleyball took place.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 1920, new jetties in Santa Monica, California created a large sandy area for public enjoyment.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] This planted the seed for beach volleyball development in that region.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The first permanent nets began to appear, and people soon began playing recreational games on public parts of the beach and in private beach clubs.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Eleven such beach clubs appeared in the Santa Monica area, beginning in late 1922.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The first inter-club competitions were staged in 1924.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Most of these early beach volleyball matches were played with teams of at least six players per side, much like indoor volleyball.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The concept of the modern two-man beach volleyball game is credited to Paul "Pablo" Johnson of the Santa Monica Athletic Club.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In the summer of 1930, while waiting for players to show up for a six-man game at the Santa Monica Athletic Club, Johnson decided to try playing with only the four people present, forming two two-man teams for the first recorded beach volleyball doubles game.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The players realized that with fewer players on the court, a taller player's height advantage could be neutralized by a shorter player's speed and ball control.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The popularity of the two-man game spread to other nearby beach clubs and eventually to the public courts.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The two-player version of the game is the most widely played version as well as the only one contested at an elite level.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beach volleyball grew in popularity in the United States during the Great Depression in the 1930s as it was an inexpensive activity.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The sport also began to appear in Europe during this time.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] By the 1940s, doubles tournaments were being played on the beaches of Santa Monica for trophies.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 1948 the first tournament to offer a prize was held in Los Angeles.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] It awarded the best teams with a case of Pepsi.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In the 1960s, an attempt to start a professional volleyball league was made in Santa Monica.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] It failed, but a professional tournament was held in France for 30,000 French francs.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In the 1950s, the first Brazilian beach volleyball tournament was held, sponsored by a newspaper publishing company.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The first Manhattan Beach Open was held in 1960, a tournament which grew in prestige to become, in the eyes of some, the "Wimbledon of Beach Volleyball".
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In the meantime, beach volleyball gained popularity: in the 1960s The Beatles tried playing in Los Angeles and US president John F.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 1974, there was an indoor tournament: "The $1500.00 World Indoor Two-Man Volleyball Championship" played in front of 4,000 volleyball enthusiast at the San Diego Sports Arena.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Fred Zuelich teamed with Dennis Hare to defeat Ron Von Hagen and Matt Gage in the championship match, Winston Cigarettes was the sponsor.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Dennis Hare went on to write the first book on the subject of beach volleyball: *The Art of Beach Volleyball*.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The first professional beach volleyball tournament was the Olympia World Championship of Beach Volleyball, staged on Labor Day weekend, 1976, at Will Rogers State Beach in Pacific Palisades, California.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The event was organized by David Wilk of *Volleyball* magazine, based in Santa Barbara.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The winners, the first "world champions", were Greg Lee and Jim Menges.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] They split US$2,500 out of a total prize purse of US$5,000.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In following years the tour expanded nationally and was renamed the Pro Beach Volleyball Tour.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] It consisted of five events in California and tournaments in Florida, Colorado, and Chicago.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] By 1984, the Pro Beach consisted of 16 events around the country and had a total prize purse of US$300,000.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] At the end of the year, however, Event Concepts was forced out of the sport by a players' strike at the World Championship and the Association of Volleyball Professionals (AVP) was founded.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 1987 the Women's Professional Volleyball Association was founded and lasted until 1997 when the women joined the AVP tour.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] At the professional level, the sport remained fairly obscure until the 1980s when beach volleyball experienced a surge in popularity with high-profile players such as Sinjin Smith, Randy Stoklos, and Karch Kiraly.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Kiraly won an Olympic gold medal in beach volleyball in its first Olympic appearance in 1996, adding that to the two Olympic golds he won as part of the USA men's indoor team, In the 1980s, the sport gained popularity on the beaches of Copacabana and Ipanema in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 1986, the first international beach volleyball exhibition was held in Rio de Janeiro with 5,000 spectators.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 1987, the first international FIVB-sanctioned tournament was played on Ipanema beach in Rio de Janeiro, with a prize purse of US$22,000.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] It was won by Sinjin Smith and Randy Stoklos.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 1989, the first FIVB-sanctioned international circuit, called the World Series, was organized with men's tournaments in Brazil, Italy and Japan.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The FIVB and its continental confederations began organizing worldwide professional tournaments and laid the groundwork for the sport's Olympic debut in 1996.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The first FIVB Beach Volleyball World Championships and FIVB Beach Volleyball World Tour were held the following year.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] By 1998, the sport had been added to other multi-sport events including the Pan American Games, Central American Games, Southeast Asian Games, Goodwill Games and Universiade.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 2001, the FIVB began organizing the annual FIVB Beach Volleyball U21 World Championships, with the annual FIVB Beach Volleyball U19 World Championships beginning the following year.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The Fédération Internationale de Volleyball (FIVB) is the international governing body for the sport.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The FIVB publishes the Official Beach Volleyball Rules every four years, as approved by the FIVB congress, which provides the framework for how beach volleyball is played internationally.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The rules have changed through the years: the court size became smaller, side out scoring was replaced by rally scoring and let serves were allowed.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beach volleyball differs from indoor, especially in requiring "clean hands" while setting.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In other words, both of your hands have to contact the ball during the set at the same time.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The ball can also not be caught or thrown, otherwise, the referee will call your set a "double" or "lift".
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beach volleyball is played on a rectangular sand court.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The court is 16 m (52.5 ft) long and 8 m (26.2 ft) wide, surrounded by a clear space, which is at least 3 m (9.8 ft) wide on all sides.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The minimum height clearance for beach volleyball courts is 7 m (23.0 ft).
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The sand should be as leveled as possible and free of potential hazards such as rocks that could cause injuries to players.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The court is divided into equal halves by a net that is 8.5 m (27.9 ft) long and 1 m (3 ft 3.4 in) wide.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The top of the net is 2.43 m (7 ft 11 11⁄16 in) above the center of the court for men's competition, and 2.24 m (7 ft 4 3⁄16 in) for women's competition, varied for veterans and junior competitions.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] An antenna, 1.8 m (5 ft 10.9 in) long and 20 mm (0.8 in) in diameter, is attached to each side edge of the net.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The antennas are considered part of the net and extend 80 cm (31.5 in) above it, forming the lateral boundaries within which the ball is allowed to cross.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Two side lines and two end lines, measuring 5 cm (2.0 in) wide, delineate the playing court.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] FIVB regulations state that the ball must be spherical and made of water resistant, flexible material, such that it is appropriate for outdoor conditions.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A beach volleyball ball has a circumference of 66–68 cm, a weight of 260–280 g and an inside pressure of 0.175–0.225 kg/cm2.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 2022, the official ball of the AVP (Association of Volleyball Professionals) tour is the Wilson OPTX AVP, and the official ball of the FIVB (Fédération Internationale de Volleyball) beach volleyball tour is the Mikasa VLS300.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] This ball was replaced with the new Mikasa Beach Pro BV550C, and was introduced in 2023.This ball was also used in the 2024 Paris Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A team is composed exclusively of two players, who must always be in play and who cannot be subjected to any substitutions or replacement.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] At the moment the ball is hit by the server, each team must be within its own court (with the exception of the server), but there are no determined positions on the court, such that no positional faults can be committed.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A team scores a point when: the ball lands on the opposing team's court; the opposing team hits the ball "out"; the opposing team commits a fault; or the opposing team receives a penalty.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The team that won the point serves for the next point.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A set is won by the first team to reach 21 points (15 points in the deciding final set) with a two-point advantage.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Thus, if the score is 20–all (or 14–all in a final set) or at any tie hereafter, whoever scores two straight points wins.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A match is won by whoever wins two sets.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A fault is committed when a referee judges that a team has made a playing action that violates the rules.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] When a team commits a fault, the opposing team receives a point and gains the right to serve.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] If both teams commit a fault simultaneously, the point is replayed.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In the 2001 season, the FIVB began testing rule changes to the court size and scoring system.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The Association of Volleyball Professionals (AVP) adopted the FIVB's rule changes that same year, which upset many of the sport's purists at the time.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The new rules were officially adopted by the FIVB in 2002.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beach volleyball is fundamentally similar to indoor volleyball.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] However, there are several differences between the two games that affect players' strategies, gameplay and techniques.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The teams start on opposite sides of the net.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] One team is designated the *serving* team and opposing team is the *receiving* team.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A coin toss is conducted by the referee before the warm-ups to determine which team serves first and which sides of the court the teams start on for the first two sets.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] If a third deciding set is needed, another coin toss will be conducted prior to the third set.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The service order decided at the coin toss before a set is maintained throughout the set.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] For each point, a player from the serving team initiates the *serve* by tossing the ball into the air and attempting to hit the ball so it passes over the net on a course such that it will land in the opposing team's court.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The opposing team must use a combination of no more than three contacts with the ball to return the ball to the opponent's side of the net, and individual players may not touch the ball twice consecutively except after a block touch.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The team with possession of the ball that is trying to attack the ball as described is said to be on *offense*.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The team on *defense* attempts to prevent the attacking team from directing the ball into their court: a player at the net jumps and reaches above the top (and if possible, across the plane) of the net to *block* the attacked ball.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] If the ball is hit around, above, or through the block, the defensive player positioned behind the blocker attempts to control the ball with a *dig* (usually a forearm pass).
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] After a successful dig, the team transitions to offense.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The game continues in this manner, rallying back and forth, until the ball touches the court or until a fault is committed.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Teams switch ends of the court after every seven points (sets 1 and 2) and five points (set 3) played.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] There is a technical time-out when the total points of both teams add up to 21.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Each team may also request one additional time-out per set.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] While there are no fixed positions, competitive players generally have specialized defensive and offensive roles.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Some competitive teams have no specializations, with the two players taking turns blocking and playing defense.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] This style of play is known as **split blocking** and allows teams to conserve energy since the demand for energy on the sand is higher.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] On offense, players tend to specialize in playing on either the **right side** or **left side** of the court.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] This allows for greater consistency in receiving serve and shot selection.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Left-handed players generally prefer to play on the right side while right-handed players generally prefer to play on the left side, as it is easier to spike a ball that has not passed across the line of one's body.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A player who is playing on the opposite side of their handedness is said to be playing on the on-hand side, while a player playing on the same side as their handedness is playing on the off-hand side.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The ball may touch any part of the body (except during the serve, when only the hand or arm may make contact), but must be hit, not caught or thrown.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] During a hit, a player may only make contact with the ball one time.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] When two players from the same team contact the ball simultaneously, it is counted as two hits, and either player may make the next contact.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] When two players from opposing teams contact the ball simultaneously over the net, in what is known as a **joust**, the team whose side the ball ends up on is entitled to another three contacts.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] When receiving a ball overhand with fingers from a hit that is not hard driven, the ball must be contacted "cleanly".
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] If a player receives the ball open-handed, the contact of each hand with the ball must be exactly simultaneous.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In practice, this means that serves are never received open-handed.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] When receiving an opponent's hard-driven attack, a double contact (provided both contacts occur in a single action) and/or a slight lift of the ball is allowed.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In particular, in defensive action of a hard driven ball, the ball can be held momentarily overhand with the fingers.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Attack-hits using an "open-handed tip or dink" directing the ball with the fingers are illegal, as are attack-hits using an overhand pass to direct the ball on a trajectory not perpendicular to the line of the shoulders (overhand passes which accidentally cross over the net are an exception).
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] These differences between the rules of indoor volleyball and beach volleyball strongly affect tactics and techniques.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beach volleyball players use hand signals to indicate to their partners the type of block they either intend to make (if they are the designated blocker) or that they want their partner to make (if they are the designated defender).
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Block signals are important so that both the blocker and defender know which area of the court is their responsibility to cover.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Block signals are made behind the back to hide them from the opposing team.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] They are usually given with both hands by the serving player's partner prior to the serve, with the left hand referring to the type of block that should be put up against the left-side attacker, and the right hand similarly referring to the right-side attacker.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A player may also "wiggle" or "flash" one block signal to indicate which opponent to serve to.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Block signals may also be given during a rally while the opposing team is preparing their attack.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Note: For some teams, closed fist and open hand signals have the opposite meaning of blocking.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] If the partner is showing the closed fist the blocker should block "ball" and open hand means that the blocker should "pull off" the net.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] There are several basic skills competitive players need to master: serving, passing, setting, attacking, blocking, and digging.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Serving is the act of putting the ball into play by striking it with the hand or arm from behind the rear court boundary.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] It can take the form of an underhand serve or an overhand serve, and examples include: float serve, jump-float serve, top-spin serve, jump serve, sky ball serve and reverse sky ball serve.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] As beach volleyball is usually played outdoors, the direction and speed of the wind and the position of the sun are considered when choosing which serve to use.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Wind can significantly affect the trajectory of a serve and so players can employ different serving strategies to take advantage of the wind conditions.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] For example, players may choose a top-spin serve when serving into the wind, causing the ball to drop short in front of the passer.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Players can also take advantage of the position of the sun.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] For example, a sky ball serve is especially effective at high noon, because the sun gets into the passer's eyes and can cause the passer to become disoriented.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Another factor the server considers is choosing which of the two opposing players to serve the ball to.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Because of the three-contact rule, the player who receives the serve will likely also be the attacker, and serving strategies can thus target an opposing player's relative weakness in passing, setting or attacking.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Although the serve can be used as an offensive weapon, most rallies are won by the receiving team, as they have the first attack opportunity.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The pass is the first of a team's 3 allowed contacts.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In indoor volleyball, passing involves two main techniques: forearm pass, or **bump**, where the ball touches the inside part of the joined forearms or platform, at waist line; and overhand pass, where it is handled with the fingertips, like a hand set, above the head.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] However, unlike indoors you may not double contact the first ball using overhand with fingers action on the beach.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In practice, this means that bump pass is much more popular in beach volleyball; similarly, beach players rarely use an overhand passing motion as the first (except on a hard driven attack) or last of the three allowed team contacts.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] **Digging** is a similar skill to passing, but the term is not used to describe receiving the serve or a free ball, but rather refers to an attempt to prevent an opponent's attack hit from touching the court.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The set is the second team contact, and its purpose is to position the ball for an attack on the third hit.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Similar to a pass, the ball can be set with either a forearm pass technique, known as a **bump set**, or an overhand pass technique, known as a **hand set**.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Due to the environmental factors that make it harder to hand set a ball "cleanly", the bump set is more common in the beach game.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] When hand setting, the player's hands must contact the ball simultaneously.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] If a referee determines that a double-hit has occurred, the point will be given to the other team.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Excessive spin after a ball has been set is often used as an indicator of a double contact fault, but causing a ball to spin while setting is not explicitly prohibited.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] After completing the contact, the setter typically turns their attention to the defense and communicates to their partner whether a blocker is up and which area of the court is open.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The second contact can also be used to attack the ball, known as an "over-on-two" attack.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A beach volleyball attack can be categorized as either a **spike** or a **shot**.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A spike involves hitting the ball hard with one open hand on a downward trajectory from above the top of the net.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A shot is a relatively soft attack used to place a ball into an open (undefended) area of the court.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Unlike indoor volleyball, a wide variety of shots are utilized in beach volleyball due to the fewer defenders on court.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A block can be used to: score a direct point by directing an attack back into the opponent's court; channel an attack to the defender by "taking away" part of the court; or slow down the ball so the defender has time to chase it down.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] At the competitive level, blockers will often reach across the net and "penetrate" the opposing team's side as much as possible to take away more hitting angles.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Blockers may also attempt a shot block, where instead of maximum penetration across the net, the blocker reaches with their hands as high as possible to achieve maximum height above the net.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Players often decide against blocking (if the opposing team's pass and set are not in a good position to produce a spike attack) and instead opt to retreat and play defense.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] This skill is known as **peeling**, **dropping** or **pulling** off the net, and is almost exclusive to beach volleyball.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Training in beach volleyball typically combines technical repetition of the core contacts (serve, pass, set, attack, block and dig) with practice tasks designed to resemble match play and its constraints, including wind and sun.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A common structure is to start with a warm-up, progress to targeted skill work, and then integrate those skills into serve–receive, transition and modified-game situations so that players practice decision-making and partner coordination under realistic conditions.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The warm-up is commonly described as serving multiple functions: preparing the body for high-level performance, reducing injury risk and allowing athletes to adjust to current environmental conditions, with ball activities used to help players calibrate to wind effects.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Coaching materials also describe progression by level.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] For beginners, emphasis is often placed on movement in sand, sustaining rallies and learning how environmental factors affect ball flight, sometimes using simple throw–catch or passing challenges to provide immediate feedback and encourage reading of the conditions.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] For intermediate and advanced athletes, practice may shift toward more specific skill objectives and higher-intensity sequences, while keeping injury-prevention and physical readiness as ongoing priorities.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Some coaching resources also advocate training methods that prioritize representative, game-like scenarios over isolated drills, such as small-sided games, modified court dimensions or target zones, and constraint-based rules that force players to adapt their solutions.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The primary international governing body for beach volleyball is the Fédération Internationale de Volleyball (FIVB).
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In the United States, USA Volleyball is the governing body for beach volleyball, as well as indoor and sitting volleyball.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Until 2021 the FIVB Beach Volleyball World Tour was the international professional tour for both men and women organized by the Fédération Internationale de Volleyball (FIVB).
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 2022 the FIVB Beach Volleyball World Tour was replaced by the Volleyball World Beach Pro Tour.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The inaugural tour of the FIVB Beach Volleyball World Tour was held in 1997, replacing the FIVB Beach Volleyball World Series that began in 1989 for men and 1992 for women.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] World Tour tournaments are ranked from 1 to 5 stars, with 5-star tournaments offering the most prize money.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The 2018 World Tour has 47 international tournaments with a total prize purse of over US$7 million.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Competing in the World Tour as well as other FIVB-recognized tournaments such as the Summer Olympics allows players to earn FIVB Ranking Points, with higher-star events being worth more points.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The World Tour concludes with the World Tour Finals at the end of each season.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The Volleyball World Beach Pro Tour comprises three level of competition: Elite, Challenge and Futures.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The FIVB also organizes the FIVB Beach Volleyball World Championships every two years, held since 1997.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The World Championships have a 48-team main draw and prize purse of US$500,000 per gender.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Players can only participate in the Continental Tour that their national federation is a member of.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In addition to prize money, Continental Tour events award players with FIVB ranking points and their national federations with National Federation ranking points.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The latter determines how many teams a national federation can send to the World Championships and the Summer Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Some countries also have domestic professional tours, but only FIVB-approved national tours can award FIVB ranking points.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] As of 2017, there are 21 FIVB-approved national tours.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In the United States, the Association of Volleyball Professionals (AVP) is the main domestic professional tour, organizing tournaments annually such as the Manhattan Beach Open.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The AVP tour is not FIVB-approved and has had conflicts with the FIVB in the 1980s and 1990s over regulations and sponsorship, leading to an initial boycott of FIVB events by the top American players.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In Germany, the Techniker Beach Tour, previously known as the Smart Beach Tour, is the top domestic tour and is FIVB-approved.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] It is the organized by the German Volleyball Association and each season ends with the German Beach Volleyball Championships.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In Brazil, the FIVB-approved Brazilian Beach Volleyball Circuit (pt:Circuito Brasileiro de Voleibol de Praia) is the main national tour.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] It has been organized by the Brazilian Volleyball Confederation since 1991.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The tour consists of the main Open Circuit and a Challenger Circuit.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Each season concludes with the Superpraia championship.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Men and women's beach volleyball has been contested in the Summer Olympics since 1996.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In the 2010–2011 academic year, the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) began sponsoring women's beach volleyball, then called "sand volleyball", as an "emerging sport".
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Initially, it was sponsored only for Division II, with Division I added the following academic year.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] NCAA competition follows standard beach volleyball rules, with competitions involving five doubles-teams from each participating school.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] For a sport to classify as a championship, at least 40 schools must sponsor it.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 2015, sixty schools had teams, allowing it to become NCAA's 90th Championship sport.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beach volleyball became a fully sanctioned NCAA championship sport in the 2015–2016 school year, following votes by leaders of all three NCAA divisions to launch a single all-divisions national championship.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 2019, the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA) approved women's collegiate beach volleyball as an "emerging sport" with 16 NAIA institutions fielding teams in the 2019–2020 school year.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beach volleyball is a men's and women's championship sport in the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) and the University Athletic Association of the Philippines (UAAP).
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In the NCAA, it is contested at both the high school and college level.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The European Universities Beach Volleyball Championships are held annually as part of the European Universities Championships.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The FIVB organizes the annual U19 and U21 World Championships.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] World Championships for the U17 and U23 age-groups were previously held as well.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Teams are awarded FIVB ranking points at these Championships, but not prize money.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Instead, the winning U19 teams get a direct main draw entry into the next U21 World Championships, while the winning U21 teams get a direct main draw entry into a World Tour 4 or 5-star event of their choice.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beach volleyball is also contested at the Youth Olympic Games (since 2014).
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In 1999, the FIVB standardized beach volleyball uniforms, with the swimsuit becoming the required uniform for both men and women.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Women were required to wear two-piece bikinis, while men were required to wear shorts that were no longer than 20 cm (7.9 in) above the knees.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] According to current FIVB rules, female beach volleyball players have the option of playing in shorts or a one-piece swimsuit.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Most players, however, prefer the two-piece bikini.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] British Olympian Denise Johns claimed that the regulation uniform is intended to be "sexy" and to draw attention.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Other players have argued that the bikini is tied to the sport's "beach culture".
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] During the 2004 Summer Olympic Games, a study was conducted on the camera angles during the beach volleyball games.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] 20% of the camera angles were focused on the chest area and 17% of the angles were focused on the buttock area.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The study concludes that this implies the look of the players is having a greater impact on fans than their actual athleticism.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Some conservative cultures have expressed religious objections to the swimsuit as a uniform.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] At the 2007 South Pacific Games, rules were adjusted to require less revealing shorts and cropped sports tops.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] At the 2006 Asian Games, only one Muslim country fielded a team in the women's competition, amid concerns the uniform was inappropriate.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In early 2012, the FIVB announced it would allow shorts (maximum length 3 cm (1.2 in) above the knee) and sleeved tops at the London 2012 Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The federation spokesman said that "many of these countries have religious and cultural requirements so the uniform needed to be more flexible".
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In fact, the weather was so cold for the evening games at London 2012 that the players sometimes had to wear shirts and leggings.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beach volleyball culture includes the people, language, fashion, and life surrounding the sport of modern beach volleyball.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] With its origins in Hawaii and California, beach volleyball is strongly associated with a casual, beach-centric lifestyle.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] As it developed nearly in parallel with modern surfing, beach volleyball culture shares some similarities with surf culture.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The beach bum archetype is one such example.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Professional beach volleyball matches often have a "party atmosphere", with loud music, announcers and dancers in between points and during time-outs.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Fashion often extends from the clothing worn during play, like the bikini or boardshorts.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] And much like surfers, beach volleyball players are at the mercy of the weather; patterns of play often develop based on weather conditions like sun and wind.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Beyond professional competition, beach volleyball has developed a recreational travel culture, with casual and amateur players participating in beach volleyball camps and training holidays at coastal destinations worldwide.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] These programs typically combine coaching, skill development, and social activities, allowing players to improve their game while experiencing the sport in different international locations.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Naturists were early adopters of the game.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Records of regular games in clubs can be found as early as the 1920s.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Given the outdoor nature of naturism, a beach version of volleyball was naturally adopted.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] By the 1960s, a volleyball court could be found in almost all naturist clubs.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] A large (over 70 teams) nude volleyball tournament has been held each fall since 1971 at White Thorn Lodge in western Pennsylvania, and several smaller tournaments occur each year throughout North America.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] The most common injuries in beach volleyball are knee, ankle, shoulder and finger injuries.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Pain due to overuse of the knee, lower back, and especially shoulder is common as well, but is less prevalent than in indoor volleyball due to the soft landing surface.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Acute lost-time injuries are also relatively rare in beach volleyball compared to other team sports.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Interest in this tape has surged after American beach volleyball player and three-time Olympic gold medalist Kerri Walsh wore it at the 2008 Beijing Olympics.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] 4x4 beach volleyball is a variant of the regular two-man beach game that is popular in the United States and Brazil.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] FIVB-sanctioned matches are best of 3 sets played to 21 points (15 points in a third set tie-break), with four starting players and up to two substitutes in a team.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] 4x4 is contested at the World Beach Games.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Snow volleyball is a winter sport played by two teams on a snow court divided by a net.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Originating as a variant of beach volleyball, the rules of snow volleyball are similar to the beach game, with the main differences being the playing surface, the scoring system and the number of players.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] As in the beach version, matches were originally best of 3 sets played to 21 points, with two players in a team.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] In December 2018, the FIVB approved new rules for snow volleyball which changed the scoring system to a best of 3 sets played to 15 points, and the number of players to three starters and one substitute in a team.
[src:beach-volleyball/beach-volleyball] Another difference is that unlike beach volleyball, a touch off block does not count as one of the three allowed touches, and any player may make the subsequent touch after the block.
